In teaching economics, I follow two core principles: clarity and learning by doing.
First, I aim to break down complex theories into clear and simple explanations without losing their meaning. As Albert Einstein said, “Everything should be made as simple as possible, but not simpler.”
This guides how I teach both the intuition and formalism behind economic ideas.
I also draw on Hans Hofmann’s belief that “the ability to simplify means to eliminate the unnecessary so that the necessary may speak,” focusing my lessons on key principles and avoiding distractions.
In practice, this means teaching in two “languages”: one as an economist using precise, technical terms, and another in everyday language that connects to students' intuition.
I see myself as a translator—economics deals with familiar ideas like trade-offs and incentives, but its language can be both confusing and powerful. My goal is to help students become fluent in both.

Second, I believe students learn best by doing.
Economics is not something you absorb passively; it becomes meaningful when students apply it.
When I taught an undergraduate class in Summer 2023, I reserved the last 30 minutes of each 1 hour and 50 minute session for active problem-solving.
Students worked through exercises on the board while I offered guidance and asked probing questions.
We also reviewed homework and exams together, using them as opportunities to reinforce concepts and clarify mistakes.
To my surprise, students gave very positive feedback on these activities, saying they helped them better understand the material and gain confidence in using it.
These moments helped students connect the lecture material to concrete applications and built their ability to think independently.

By combining clear explanations with active practice, I aim to equip students with both a strong conceptual foundation and the tools to apply economic reasoning beyond the classroom.
My broader goal is to help students not just learn economics, but learn how to use economics to understand the world.

